{
  "page": "Languages",
  "html": "<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Throughout <i><a href=\"/index.php/A_Song_of_Ice_and_Fire\" title=\"A Song of Ice and Fire\">A Song of Ice and Fire</a></i>, numerous cultural and regional dialects are discussed. These dialects form the <a href=\"/index.php/Known_world\" title=\"Known world\">known world</a>'s spoken tongue, and help define its people.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Languages_of_Westeros\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Languages of Westeros</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Languages_of_Essos\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Languages of Essos</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Non-Human_Communication\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Non-Human Communication</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Portrayal\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Portrayal</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Languages_of_Westeros\">Languages of Westeros</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/index.php?title=Languages&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" class=\"tw-editsection-onhover\" title=\"Edit section: Languages of Westeros\"><span class=\"glyphicon glyphicon-pencil\"></span> </a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The <a href=\"/index.php/Old_Tongue\" title=\"Old Tongue\">Old Tongue</a> was the language of the <a href=\"/index.php/First_Men\" title=\"First Men\">First Men</a>, who dominated <a href=\"/index.php/Westeros\" title=\"Westeros\">Westeros</a> for thousands of years. Today, the Old Tongue is still remembered by <a href=\"/index.php/Giants\" title=\"Giants\">giants</a> and some <a href=\"/index.php/Free_folk\" title=\"Free folk\">free folk</a> who live <a href=\"/index.php/Beyond_the_Wall\" title=\"Beyond the Wall\">beyond the Wall</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Racok51.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Racok51.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Rasos15.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Rasos15.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> but most people within the <a href=\"/index.php/Seven_Kingdoms\" title=\"Seven Kingdoms\">Seven Kingdoms</a> know no other language than the <a href=\"/index.php/Common_Tongue\" title=\"Common Tongue\">Common Tongue</a>. Although the Common Tongue has minor variations and regional accents,<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Ragot26.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ragot26.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/index.php/Dornishmen\" title=\"Dornishmen\">Dornishmen</a> can communicate with <a href=\"/index.php/Northmen\" title=\"Northmen\">northmen</a> without difficulty. Foreign tongues are taught in the <a href=\"/index.php/Citadel\" title=\"Citadel\">Citadel</a> and by <a href=\"/index.php/Maesters\" title=\"Maesters\">maesters</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Radwd1.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Radwd1.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> or are brought from other lands by immigrants, merchants, sellswords, and the like.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Languages_of_Essos\">Languages of Essos</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/index.php?title=Languages&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" class=\"tw-editsection-onhover\" title=\"Edit section: Languages of Essos\"><span class=\"glyphicon glyphicon-pencil\"></span> </a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Many languages exist in <a href=\"/index.php/Essos\" title=\"Essos\">Essos</a>, the continent across the <a href=\"/index.php/Narrow_sea\" title=\"Narrow sea\">narrow sea</a>. \n</p>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/index.php/High_Valyrian\" title=\"High Valyrian\">High Valyrian</a>, the language of the old <a href=\"/index.php/Valyrian_Freehold\" title=\"Valyrian Freehold\">Valyrian Freehold</a>, is learned by well-educated men across many of its former territories and beyond. In the four centuries since Valyria's destruction, everyday use led the language spoken in different former provinces to grow into a dozen bastardized dialects from the <a href=\"/index.php/Free_Cities\" title=\"Free Cities\">Free Cities</a> to <a href=\"/index.php/Slaver%27s_Bay\" title=\"Slaver&#39;s Bay\">Slaver's Bay</a>, known as \"Low Valyrian\". Each Free City's dialect is on its way to be a separate language,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Radwd1.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Radwd1.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> but someone who is fluent in High Valyrian can communicate well enough.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Radwd6.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Radwd6.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The <a href=\"/index.php/Dothraki_language\" title=\"Dothraki language\">Dothraki language</a> is the tongue of the <a href=\"/index.php/Dothraki\" title=\"Dothraki\">Dothraki</a>, the indigenous inhabitants of the <a href=\"/index.php/Dothraki_sea\" title=\"Dothraki sea\">Dothraki sea</a>.</li>\n<li><a href=\"/index.php/Lhazareen\" title=\"Lhazareen\">Lhazareen</a> is described as singsong.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ragot61.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ragot61.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/index.php/Old_Ghiscari\" title=\"Old Ghiscari\">Old Ghiscari</a> is a largely extinct tongue. It was spoken five thousand years ago by the <a href=\"/index.php/Ghiscari\" title=\"Ghiscari\">Ghiscari</a> people of the <a href=\"/index.php/Old_Empire_of_Ghis\" title=\"Old Empire of Ghis\">Old Empire of Ghis</a>, which was destroyed by the <a href=\"/index.php/Valyrian_Freehold\" title=\"Valyrian Freehold\">Valyrian Freehold</a>. A <a href=\"/index.php/Mongrel_Ghiscari\" title=\"Mongrel Ghiscari\">mongrel tongue</a> blending High Valyrian and Old Ghiscari is now the predominant language of <a href=\"/index.php/Slaver%27s_Bay\" title=\"Slaver&#39;s Bay\">Slaver's Bay</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Radwd14.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Radwd14.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Radwd60.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Radwd60.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> though Old Ghiscari is still spoken by some, and engraved Ghiscari glyphs can be found on various old objects.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Rasos23.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_10-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Rasos23.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The <a href=\"/index.php/Summer_Tongue\" title=\"Summer Tongue\">Summer Tongue</a> is used in the <a href=\"/index.php/Summer_Isles\" title=\"Summer Isles\">Summer Isles</a>.</li>\n<li>The <a href=\"/index.php/Ibbenese_language\" title=\"Ibbenese language\">Ibbenese language</a> is a \"guttural, grunting tongue\" spoken by the <a href=\"/index.php/Ibbenese\" title=\"Ibbenese\">Ibbenese</a> in <a href=\"/index.php/Ibben\" title=\"Ibben\">Ibben</a> and northern Essos.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Rtwoiafbeyond_the_free_cities:_ib.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_11-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Rtwoiafbeyond_the_free_cities:_ib.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The <a href=\"/index.php/Speech_of_Asshai\" title=\"Speech of Asshai\">speech of Asshai</a> can be used in <a href=\"/index.php/Spells\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Spells\">spells</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Racok10.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_12-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Racok10.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The <a href=\"/index.php/Trade_talk\" title=\"Trade talk\">trade talk</a> is a coarse argot that has developed across most of the world's major ports, using words from a dozen languages (many of them insults) and hand gestures.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Raffc34.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_13-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Raffc34.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Radwd47.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_14-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Radwd47.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The <a href=\"/index.php/Rhoynish_language\" title=\"Rhoynish language\">Rhoynish language</a> was spoken by the <a href=\"/index.php/Rhoynar\" title=\"Rhoynar\">Rhoynar</a>. The <a href=\"/index.php/Red_Princes\" title=\"Red Princes\">Red Princes</a> of <a href=\"/index.php/Dorne\" title=\"Dorne\">Dorne</a> attempted to outlaw its use after their migration to Westeros, but it is said that the <a href=\"/index.php/Orphans_of_the_Greenblood\" title=\"Orphans of the Greenblood\">orphans of the Greenblood</a> continue to speak it in private.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Rtwoiafdorne:_queer_customs_of_the_south.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_15-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Rtwoiafdorne:_queer_customs_of_the_south.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Non-Human_Communication\">Non-Human Communication</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/index.php?title=Languages&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" class=\"tw-editsection-onhover\" title=\"Edit section: Non-Human Communication\"><span class=\"glyphicon glyphicon-pencil\"></span> </a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>The <a href=\"/index.php/Children_of_the_forest\" title=\"Children of the forest\">children of the forest</a> speak and sing in the <a href=\"/index.php/True_Tongue\" title=\"True Tongue\">True Tongue</a>, and have taught it to some <a href=\"/index.php/Raven\" title=\"Raven\">ravens</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Radwd13.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_16-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Radwd13.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Radwd34.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_17-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Radwd34.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-17\">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The <a href=\"/index.php/Others\" title=\"Others\">Others</a>' language is described as sounding like cracking of ice on a winter lake.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ragotprologue.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_18-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ragotprologue.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-18\">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> In <i><a href=\"/index.php/Game_of_Thrones\" title=\"Game of Thrones\">Game of Thrones</a></i> it is named <a href=\"/index.php/Skroth\" title=\"Skroth\">Skroth</a>.</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Portrayal\">Portrayal</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/index.php?title=Languages&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" class=\"tw-editsection-onhover\" title=\"Edit section: Portrayal\"><span class=\"glyphicon glyphicon-pencil\"></span> </a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Unlike <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._R._R._Tolkien\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"w:J. R. R. Tolkien\">J. R. R. Tolkien</a>, who created entire languages with grammar, syntax, and tenses, <a href=\"/index.php/George_R._R._Martin\" title=\"George R. R. Martin\">George R. R. Martin</a> has created only a few words from each language in his world, and his languages are not conveyed in any great detail. Instead, the tongue in which they are speaking is noted but rendered in English, with added characteristics and flavor portrayed through out the text. As Martin explained,\n</p>\n<blockquote class=\"templatequote\" style=\"border-left:none;\"><div class=\"templatequotetext\"><p>Tolkien was a philologist, and an Oxford don, and could spend decades laboriously inventing <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvish_languages_(Middle-earth)\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"w:Elvish languages (Middle-earth)\">Elvish</a> in all its detail. I, alas, am only a hardworking SF and fantasy novel, and I don't have his gift for languages. That is to say, I have not actually created a <a href=\"/index.php/High_Valyrian\" title=\"High Valyrian\">Valyrian language</a>. The best I could do was try to sketch in each of the chief tongues of my imaginary world in broad strokes, and give them each their characteristic sounds and spellings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-19\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-19\">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup></p></div>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_J._Peterson\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"w:David J. Peterson\">David J. Peterson</a> developed spoken <a href=\"/index.php/Dothraki_language\" title=\"Dothraki language\">Dothraki</a> and High Valyrian for HBO's television adaptation, <i><a href=\"/index.php/Game_of_Thrones\" title=\"Game of Thrones\">Game of Thrones</a></i>. The languages expand greatly from Martin's few created words. A website, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.dothraki.org/\">dothraki.org</a>, helps teach and spread the constructed tongues. The popularity of the Dothraki language has led it to be called \"the new <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klingon_language\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"w:Klingon language\">Klingon</a>\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-20\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-20\">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>Peterson was given considerably leeway, as he was not strictly hired as linguist for just TV adaptations but also for place name adaptations used in <i><a href=\"/index.php/The_Lands_of_Ice_and_Fire\" title=\"The Lands of Ice and Fire\">The Lands of Ice and Fire</a></i> map book. He worked on these projects in consultation with Martin, thus several worldbuilding points about how languages are related to each other might be regarded as semi-canon. \n</p><p>Peterson inferred that the Dothraki and Lhazareen share common ancestry, given that the Lhazareen are said to closely resemble the Dothraki but are generally shorter. Thus he developed an outline for an ancestral \"Proto-Plains\" language which their current languages branched off from. Peterson likened the relationship between Dothraki and Lhazareen to the difference between English and Swedish.<sup id=\"cite_ref-21\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-21\">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Similarly, Peterson developed an outline for how the different Low Valyrian dialects that diverged from High Valyrian are related to each other, much like how the real-life Romance languages diverged from classical Latin. There are three broad groupings or branches:<sup id=\"cite_ref-22\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-22\">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<ul><li>Ghiscari Low Valyrian (or Eastern Low Valyrian) - spoken in Slaver's Bay, and thus the only branch Peterson was able to develop for <i>Game of Thrones</i> itself. This group was heavily influenced by the extinct Old Ghiscari language.</li>\n<li>Southern Low Valyrian - spoken in the southern Free Cities, from Volantis to Myr. These dialects are the least divergent from High Valyrian, and fairly similar to each other.</li>\n<li>Northern Low Valyrian - spoken in the northern Free Cities, which due to their geographic isolation at the distant frontier of the Valyrian Freehold and disparate origins are quite divergent from High Valyrian as well as from each other. Norvos, Qohor, and Lorath were founded by religious dissidents from Valyria who struck out on their own, Pentos had strong influence from local Andals; most of all, Braavos was founded by a hodge-podge of escaped slaves taken to Valyria from across the world and thus had many disparate influences (thus while Volantene is closest to High Valyrian, Braavosi is the most divergent).</li></ul>\n<p>Peterson also made a brief outline for Old Tongue, a thin gloss for a simplified version spoken by the Giants called \"Mag Nuk\". Peterson actually developed a fairly detailed version of the language used by the Children of the Forest, originally meant to be used in <i>Game of Thrones</i> Season 6 but which ultimately never appeared on-screen.\n</p><p>Peterson continued to expand on High Valyrian for <i>House of the Dragon</i> - and starting in its first season also developed a complex glyph writing system that appears on-screen.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/index.php?title=Languages&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" class=\"tw-editsection-onhover\" title=\"Edit section: External links\"><span class=\"glyphicon glyphicon-pencil\"></span> </a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://wiki.languageinvention.com/index.php?title=Main_Page\">Language Invention Wiki</a> - devoted to the conlangs developed by David J. Peterson</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/index.php?title=Languages&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" class=\"tw-editsection-onhover\" title=\"Edit section: References\"><span class=\"glyphicon glyphicon-pencil\"></span> </a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"references-small\" style=\"-webkit-column-width:200px; -moz-column-width:200px; column-width:200px; -webkit-column-count:2; -moz-column-count:2; column-count:2;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Racok51.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><a href=\"#cite_ref-Racok51.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_1-0\">↑</a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i><a href=\"/index.php/A_Clash_of_Kings\" title=\"A Clash of Kings\">A Clash of Kings</a></i>, <a href=\"/index.php/A_Clash_of_Kings-Chapter_51\" title=\"A Clash of Kings-Chapter 51\">Chapter 51</a>, Jon VI.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Rasos15.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><a href=\"#cite_ref-Rasos15.7B.7B.7B3.7D.7D.7D.7B.7B.7B4.7D.7D.7D_2-0\">↑</a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i><a href=\"/index.php/A_Storm_of_Swords\" title=\"A Storm of Swords\">A Storm of Swords</a></i>, <a href=\"/index.php/A_Storm_of_Swords-Chapter_15\" title=\"A Storm of Swords-Chapter 15\">Chapter 15</a>, Jon II.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">↑</a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/index.php/So_Spake_Martin\" title=\"So Spake Martin\">So Spake Martin</a>: <a class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.westeros.org/Citadel/SSM/Entry/2802\">Cyvasse, Acc